The paper discusses the computational power and complexity of the General Purpose Analog Computer (GPAC), which is a mathematical model of continuous-time analog machines. This topic falls under the scope of scientific computing (cs.SC) and numerical analysis (cs.NA). The paper also explores the notion of computation and time/space complexity, which are fundamental topics in computer science theory (cs.DS). The GPAC is a system that involves differential equations, which is a topic in control systems (cs.SY) and optimization (cs.LO).
